newsitem.title: USA: CME live cattle end up, feeders close mixed.
newsitem.headline: CME live cattle end up, feeders close mixed.

text.p: CME live cattle ended with modest gains despite a $1.00 per cwt jump in the price of fed cattle and feeder cattle futures ended mixed, traders said.
Packers paid $71.00 for fed cattle in Oklahoma and Texas markets Tuesday, but traders said those gains had been anticipated by the market on Monday.
"We had already priced in $71.00 trade, that's why the market didn't respond," one cattle trader said.
Some traders attributed the modest price action in futures to traders' reluctance to step back into the market following sharp gains on Monday.
"Not everyone believes that rally was for real," one floor trader said. "The beef is not acting that well."
At midday, the U.S. Department of Agriculture reported that most grades of wholesale beef were quoted up $0.19 to down $0.31 per cwt in moderate movement of 146 loads of fabricated cuts.
Demand for beef at the retail level is expected to fall as retailers begin to book turkeys and hams for the upcoming Thanksgiving and Christmas holidays.
"This is not exactly the time of year when beef demand goes through the roof," one cattle trader said.
One prominent feedlot was a noted seller in the cattle pit and traders said commercials were also lifting hedges. Commodity funds were early buyers, they said.
December live cattle contract's discount relative to cash prices also offered traders a reason to buy futures, sources said.

December live cattle settled unchanged at 66.675 cents per lb, versus the $71.00 price packers paid for cash cattle Tuesday. Other live cattle contracts were up 0.020 to up 0.100 cent. February cattle closed up 0.025 at 63.550 cent.
Feeder cattle futures followed cattle higher, but October could not shake off weakness from a big drop in the CME feeder cattle index. The CME average feeder steer price dropped 0.88 to $61.97 cwt.
